# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: doip-diagnostics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:doip-diagnostics/automotive-ethernet] These standards are specified in Clauses 125 and 126 of the IEEE 802.3 standard.
[src:doip-diagnostics/automotive-ethernet] The physical (PHY) layer transmission technology of IEEE 802.3bz is based on 10GBASE-T, but operates at a lower signaling rate.
[src:doip-diagnostics/automotive-ethernet] By reducing the original signal rate to 1⁄4 or 1⁄2, the link speed drops to 2.5 or 5 Gbit/s, respectively.
[src:doip-diagnostics/automotive-ethernet] The spectral bandwidth of the signal is reduced accordingly, lowering the requirements on the cabling, so that 2.5GBASE-T and 5GBASE-T can be deployed at a cable length of up to 100 m on Cat 5e or better cables.
[src:doip-diagnostics/automotive-ethernet] The NBASE-T effort also standardized how its switches can implement power over Ethernet according to the IEEE 802.3at and successor standards.
[src:doip-diagnostics/automotive-ethernet] This allows a single cable to provide both power and data for high-bandwidth wireless access points such as those that implement the IEEE 802.11ax (Wi-Fi 6) and IEEE 802.11be (Wi-Fi 7) standards.
[src:doip-diagnostics/automotive-ethernet] Prior to the release of 2.5GBASE-T and 5GBASE-T, manufacturers of wireless access points that wanted to support multi-gigabit uplink speed using standard gigabit Ethernet ports had to include multiple Ethernet ports on their access points.
[src:doip-diagnostics/automotive-ethernet] By bonding the connections from multiple Ethernet ports via IEEE 802.3ad link aggregation or similar, manufacturers were able to achieve speeds close to 2 Gbit/s by using two ports that support gigabit speeds.
[src:doip-diagnostics/automotive-ethernet] This would require the wireless access point to be connected to the rest of the network with 2 Ethernet cables and require both the wireless access point and network hardware to support and be configured for link aggregation.
[src:doip-diagnostics/automotive-ethernet] Wireless access points that support 2.5GBASE-T or 5GBASE-T eliminate this complexity.
[src:doip-diagnostics/automotive-ethernet] In 2013 with the release of IEEE 802.11ac (Wi-Fi 5), wireless access points for the first time could reach speeds of 2 Gbit/s or 4 Gbit/s, exceeding the 1 Gbit/s IEEE 802.3ab 1000BASE-T wired Ethernet uplink.
[src:doip-diagnostics/automotive-ethernet] While 10GBASE-T had already been standardized since 2006, this standard used a higher signaling frequency that would have substantially limited the maximum distance of Cat5e cable runs.
[src:doip-diagnostics/automotive-ethernet] Therefore, there was demand for an intermediate standard that could uplink the 2 Gbit/s and 4 Gbit/s speeds from wireless access points over existing Cat5e cable.
[src:doip-diagnostics/automotive-ethernet] The development of the 2.5GBASE-T and 5GBASE-T standards enabled wireless access points to reach their maximum speeds without being limited by the Ethernet uplink speeds over a single existing Cat5e cable, while also being compatible with newer Cat6 and Cat6a cabling.
[src:doip-diagnostics/automotive-ethernet] The 2.5GBASE-T and 5GBASE-T standards also serve as an interim solution for achieving lower-cost and lower power consumption multi-gigabit network speeds.
[src:doip-diagnostics/automotive-ethernet] As of Dec 2022, 10GBASE-T network equipment is still substantially more expensive than 1GBASE-T, 2.5GBASE-T, and 5GBASE-T network equipment.
[src:doip-diagnostics/automotive-ethernet] IEEE 802.3bz also supports power over Ethernet, which had previously not been available with IEEE 802.3an 10GBASE-T.
[src:doip-diagnostics/automotive-ethernet] As early as 2013, the Intel Avoton server processors integrated 2.5 Gbit/s Ethernet ports.
[src:doip-diagnostics/automotive-ethernet] Whilst Broadcom had announced a series of 2.5 Gbit/s transceiver ICs, 2.5 Gbit/s switch hardware was not widely commercially available at that point.
[src:doip-diagnostics/automotive-ethernet] Many early 10GBASE-T switches, particularly those with SFP+ interfaces, do not support the intermediate speeds.
[src:doip-diagnostics/automotive-ethernet] In October 2014, the NBASE-T Alliance was founded, initially comprising Cisco, Aquantia, Freescale, and Xilinx.
[src:doip-diagnostics/automotive-ethernet] By December 2015, it contained more than 45 companies, and aimed to have its specification compatible with 802.3bz.
[src:doip-diagnostics/automotive-ethernet] The competing MGBASE-T Alliance, stating the same faster Gigabit Ethernet objectives, was founded in December 2014.
[src:doip-diagnostics/automotive-ethernet] In contrast to NBASE-T, the MGBASE-T said that their specifications would be open source.
[src:doip-diagnostics/automotive-ethernet] IEEE 802.3's 2.5G/5GBASE-T Task Force started working on the 2.5GBASE-T and 5GBASE-T standards in March 2015.
[src:doip-diagnostics/automotive-ethernet] The two NBASE-T and MGBASE-T Alliances ended up collaborating. with the forming of the IEEE 802.3bz Task Force under the patronage of the Ethernet Alliance in June 2015.
[src:doip-diagnostics/automotive-ethernet] On September 23, 2016, the IEEE-SA Standards Board approved IEEE Std 802.3bz-2016.
[src:doip-diagnostics/automotive-ethernet] The IEEE 802.3ch-2020 2.5GBASE-T1, 5GBASE-T1, and 10GBASE-T1 standards are derived from the IEEE 802.3bp-2016 1000BASE-T1 Ethernet over single twisted pair standard, and share very little in common with the similarly named 2.5GBASE-T and 5GBASE-T standards at the PHY layer.
[src:doip-diagnostics/automotive-ethernet] 2.5GBASE-T1, 5GBASE-T1, and 10GBASE-T1 can run over a single twisted pair up to 15 meters in length, use PAM8 modulation (compared to PAM3 modulation in 1000BASE-T1 or PAM-16 + 128DSQ in 2.5GBASE-T/5GBASE-T), and are standardized in 802.3ch-2020.
[src:doip-diagnostics/automotive-ethernet] Their primary use is in embedded automotive applications, and are commonly referred to as part of the Automotive Ethernet family of standards, along with 100BASE-T1 and 1000BASE-T1.
[src:doip-diagnostics/electronic-control-unit] An **electronic control unit** (**ECU**), also known as an **electronic control module** (**ECM**), is an embedded system in automotive electronics that controls one or more of the electrical systems or subsystems in a car or other motor vehicle.
[src:doip-diagnostics/electronic-control-unit] These ECUs together are sometimes referred to collectively as **the car's computer** though technically they are all separate computers, not a single one.
[src:doip-diagnostics/electronic-control-unit] Sometimes an assembly incorporates several individual control modules (a PCM often controls both the engine and the transmission).
[src:doip-diagnostics/electronic-control-unit] Some modern motor vehicles have up to 150 ECUs.
[src:doip-diagnostics/electronic-control-unit] Embedded software in ECUs continues to increase in line count, complexity, and sophistication.
[src:doip-diagnostics/electronic-control-unit] Managing the increasing complexity and number of ECUs in a vehicle has become a key challenge for original equipment manufacturers (OEMs).
[src:doip-diagnostics/electronic-control-unit] The development of an ECU involves both hardware and software required to perform the functions expected from that particular module.
[src:doip-diagnostics/electronic-control-unit] Automotive ECU's are being developed following the V-model.
[src:doip-diagnostics/electronic-control-unit] Recently the trend is to dedicate a significant amount of time and effort to develop safe modules by following standards like ISO 26262.
[src:doip-diagnostics/electronic-control-unit] It is rare that a module is developed fully from scratch.
[src:doip-diagnostics/electronic-control-unit] The design is generally iterative and improvements are made to both the hardware and software.
[src:doip-diagnostics/electronic-control-unit] The development of most ECUs is carried out by Tier 1 suppliers based on specifications provided by the OEM.
[src:doip-diagnostics/electronic-control-unit] As part of the development cycle, manufacturers perform detailed FMEAs and other failure analyses to catch failure modes that can lead to unsafe conditions or driver annoyance.
[src:doip-diagnostics/electronic-control-unit] Extensive testing and validation activities are carried out as part of the production part approval process to gain the confidence of the hardware and software.
[src:doip-diagnostics/electronic-control-unit] On-board diagnostics or OBD help provide specific data related to which system or component failed or caused a failure during run time and help perform repairs.
[src:doip-diagnostics/electronic-control-unit] Some people may wish to modify their ECU so as to be able to add or change functionality.
[src:doip-diagnostics/electronic-control-unit] However modern ECUs come equipped with protection locks to prevent users from modifying the circuit or exchange chips.
[src:doip-diagnostics/electronic-control-unit] The protection locks are a form of digital rights management (DRM), the circumventing of which is illegal in certain jurisdictions.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] Ethernet has since been refined to support higher bit rates, a greater number of nodes, and longer link distances, but retains much backward compatibility.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] Over time, Ethernet has largely replaced competing wired LAN technologies such as Token Ring, FDDI and ARCNET.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] The original 10BASE5 Ethernet uses a thick coaxial cable as a shared medium.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] Its immediate successor 10BASE2 uses a thinner and more flexible cable that is both less expensive and easier to use.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] More modern Ethernet variants use twisted pair and fiber optic links in conjunction with switches.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] Over the course of its history, Ethernet data transfer rates have been increased from the original 2.94 Mbit/s to the latest 800 Gbit/s, with rates up to 1.6 Tbit/s under development.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] The Ethernet standards include several wiring and signaling variants of the OSI physical layer.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] Systems communicating over Ethernet divide a stream of data into shorter pieces called frames.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] Each frame contains source and destination addresses, and error-checking data so that damaged frames can be detected and discarded; most often, higher-layer protocols trigger retransmission of lost frames.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] Per the OSI model, Ethernet provides services up to and including the data link layer.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] The 48-bit MAC address was adopted by other IEEE 802 networking standards, including IEEE 802.11 (Wi-Fi), as well as by FDDI.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] EtherType values are also used in Subnetwork Access Protocol (SNAP) headers.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] Ethernet is widely used in homes and industry, and interworks well with wireless Wi-Fi technologies.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] Ethernet commonly carries Internet Protocol traffic, and so Ethernet is considered one of the key technologies that make up the Internet.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] The original forms of Ethernet used a shared communications channel.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] This concept originated in ALOHAnet, designed in the late 1960s by Norman Abramson.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] ALOHANet was a 4800 bps radio network used by the University of Hawaii.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] When a sender detected that its message hadn't been received, it would resend the message after waiting for a randomly selected period of time.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] In 1972, Robert Metcalfe and David Boggs adapted the ALOHAnet approach to transmission over a shared coaxial cable in the Xerox Palo Alto Research Center (Xerox PARC).
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] This network connected ALTO computers using a coaxial cable.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] It first ran on May 22, 1973 with a bit rate of 2.94 Mbps.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] In a memo written at that time, Metcalfe named the concept "Ethernet." The name was inspired by the former idea that the universe was filled with a "luminiferous aether" that carried electromagnetic waves, and calling it Ethernet emphasized its ability to run over any transmission medium.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] Ethernet improved the original ALOHANet design because a sender would first listen to the channel to determine if it was already in use.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] The combination of the new idea of *Carrier Sense* with *Multiple Access* and *Collision Detection* from ALOHANet became Carrier-Sense Multiple Access/Collision Detection, or CSMA/CD.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] In 1975, Metcalfe, Boggs and their colleagues Charles Thacker and Butler Lampson filed for a patent on Ethernet, which was granted in 1977.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] By 1976, 100 ALTOs at Xerox PARC were connected using Ethernet.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] In July 1976, Metcalfe and Boggs published the seminal paper *Ethernet: Distributed Packet Switching for Local Computer Networks* in Communications of the ACM (CACM).
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] Subsequently between 1976-1978 Ron Crane, Bob Garner, Hal Murray, and Roy Ogus designed a 10Mbps version of Ethernet running over coaxial cable.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] There were multiple local area network technologies in the 1970s.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] These included IBM's Token Ring, Network Systems Corporation's HYPERchannel and Datapoint's ARCnet.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] Version 2 was published in November 1982.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] In June 1981, the Institute of Electronic and Electrical Engineers (IEEE) Project 802 (for local area network standards) created an 802.3 subcommittee to produce an Ethernet standard based on DIX.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] In 1983, a standard was published for 10 Mbps Ethernet over a coaxial cable of up to 500 meters (10BASE5).
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] It differed only in some details from the DIX standard.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] As part of the standardization process, Xerox turned over all its Ethernet patents to the IEEE, and anyone can implement 802.3.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] IEEE 802.3 is now considered the same as Ethernet.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] The cooperation of Xerox with Intel and Digital on the Ethernet standard ultimately made it a truly open standard.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] In June 1979, Metcalfe left Xerox to found the Computer, Communication, and Compatibility Corporation, better known as 3Com, along with Howard Charney, Ron Crane, Greg Shaw, and Bill Krause.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] Metcalfe's vision was to sell Ethernet adapters for all personal computers.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] Apple quickly agreed, but IBM was committed to their own LAN protocol, the Token Ring.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] Nonetheless, 3Com developed the EtherLink ISA adapter and started shipping it with DOS driver software, making it usable on IBM PCs.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] The EtherLink adapter had several advantages over competitors.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] It was the first network interface card (NIC) to use VLSI semiconductor technology (developed in partnership with Seeq Technologies).
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] This meant most of the functions, including the transceiver, could be contained on a single chip, so the price for Etherlink ($950) was significantly lower than of its competitors.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] 3Com introduced a new, thinner coaxial cable for the card, called Thin Ethernet, making it more convenient to install and use.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] Finally, Etherlink was the first Ethernet adapter for the IBM PC.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] Because both businesses and home users adopted the IBM PC, its market expanded rapidly, and by 1982, IBM was shipping 200,000 units a month.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] Since IBM hadn't realized that businesses would want the computers connected by a network, Etherlink sales filled the vacuum, and in 1984, 3Com was able to file for a public stock offering.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] The Etherlink approach was standardized by IEEE as 10BASE2 in 1984.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] Also in the early 1980s, Novell began selling Network Interface Cards (NICs) to go with its NetWare operating system.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] These NE2000 NICs were all Ethernet, and because NetWare became an important application for businesses, this increased the demand for Ethernet adapters.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] Then in 1989, Novell sold its NIC business and licensed the NE2000 card, creating a highly competitive market and driving the price of Ethernet cards down, while cards for other technologies, such as IBM's Token Ring, remained high.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] Starting in late 1983, AT&T and NCR promoted a star configuration using unshielded twisted pair cabling (UTP), or regular telephone wire.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] This became StarLAN, running at 1Mbps over cables up to 500 meters, and was standardized as 1BASE5 by IEEE 802.3, but on August 17, 1987, SynOptics introduced LATTISNET with 10Mbps Ethernet also over regular telephone wire (UTP).
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] In the fall of 1990, the IEEE issued the 802.3i standard for 10BASE-T, Ethernet over twisted pairs, and the following year, Ethernet sales nearly doubled.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] By 1992, Ethernet was the de facto standard for LANs.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] In the 1990s, the proliferation of PCs combined with their increasing power drove demand for much faster network infrastructure.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] The Kalpana EtherSwitch EPS-700 helped to meet this demand by increasing the speed of Ethernet dramatically.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] The switch allowed multiple simultaneous data transmission paths and it used faster cut-through bridging technology in place of store-and-forward.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] The switch was marketed as a way to improve network performance rather than as a way to connect different LANs, creating a new market category.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] Then in 1993, Kalpana introduced full-duplex mode for switches, potentially doubling the data transmission rate.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] In 1997, the IEEE standardized full-duplex flow-control switched in 802.3x.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] The 10Mbps rate of Ethernet was still too slow for some networks, though, and most larger networks planned to use FDDI, a very expensive alternative to Ethernet.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] In August 1991 Howard Charney, David Boggs, Ron Crane, and Larry Birenbaum founded Grand Junction Networks to build and market 100Mbps Ethernet equipment.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] Their announcement in 1992 triggered a standards war over whether to maintain backward compatibility with the original Ethernet CSMA/CD standard or to adopt a demand-priority protocol pushed by HP and AT&T.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] Since the competing groups were unable to come to an agreement, IEEE set up a new group, 802.12, for the demand-priority scheme.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] The supporters of backward compatibility formed the Fast Ethernet Alliance in 1993 to publish an interoperability specification that became the 100BASE-TX standard (also known as Fast Ethernet).
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] At the same time, Grand Junction shipped the first Fast Ethernet hubs and NICs, and more companies announced Fast Ethernet equipment.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] In 1994, Sun Microsystems, followed by 3Com, DEC, and others, shipped 100BASE-TX compliant products, and the IEEE 802.3u specification for Fast Ethernet was approved.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] Since 1999, Ethernet's maximum speed has increased with the introductions of Gigabit Ethernet (802.3ab), 2.5 and 5 Gbit/s Ethernet (802.3bz), 10 Gigabit Ethernet (802.3ae), 25 Gigabit Ethernet (802.3by), 50 Gigabit Ethernet (802.3cd), 100 Gigabit Ethernet (802.3ba), and Terabit Ethernet (802.3df).
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] In February 1980, the Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers (IEEE) started project 802 to standardize local area networks (LAN).
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] The DIX group with Gary Robinson (DEC), Phil Arst (Intel), and Bob Printis (Xerox) submitted the so-called *Blue Book* CSMA/CD specification as a candidate for the LAN specification.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] In addition to CSMA/CD, Token Ring (supported by IBM) and Token Bus (selected and henceforward supported by General Motors) were also considered as candidates for a LAN standard.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] Competing proposals and broad interest in the initiative led to strong disagreement over which technology to standardize.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] In December 1980, the group was split into three subgroups, and standardization proceeded separately for each proposal.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] The development of the CSMA/CD standard was slowed by conflict over issues such as baseband versus broadband and the lengths of address fields.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] Some members of the DIX group became impatient with the process and concerned that the ultimate CSMA/CD standard would differ significantly from their "Blue Book" de facto standard.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] They turned instead to the European Computer Manufacturers Association (ECMA), where Friedrich Röscheisen of Siemens helped to introduce the Blue Book as a candidate standard to a newly created "Local Networks" Task Group (TC24).
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] Gary Robinson later claimed to have instigated the effort to convince ECMA to standardize CSMA/CD.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] ECMA approved a standard in June 1982 that was very close to the DIX de facto standard.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] Because the DIX proposal was the most technically complete and because of the speedy action taken by ECMA, the IEEE group felt compelled to approve the 802.3 CSMA/CD standard in December 1982.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] It differed only slightly from the DIX standard in terminology and frame format.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] IEEE published the 802.3 standard as a draft in 1983 and as a standard in 1985.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] The ISO 8802-3 standard was published on March 23, 1989.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] The IEEE has approved changes to its 802.3 (Ethernet) standard regularly since 1985.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] The current standard is available from the IEEE website.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] With each change to the standard, the IEEE first issues a supplement with a letter designation added to IEEE 802.3.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] For example, IEEE 802.3u refers to Fast Ethernet.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] Then when the supplement is formally approved, it is merged with the main standard.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] Subsequent standards have provided for ever-faster versions of Ethernet, additional physical media, and network management.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] For a table of IEEE Ethernet standards, see IEEE 802.3 § Communication standards.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] Ethernet has evolved to include higher bandwidth, improved medium access control methods, and different physical media.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] The multidrop coaxial cable was replaced with physical point-to-point links connected by Ethernet repeaters or switches.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] Ethernet stations communicate by sending each other data packets: blocks of data individually sent and delivered.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] As with other IEEE 802 LANs, each adapter comes programmed with a globally unique 48-bit MAC address so that each Ethernet station has a unique address.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] The MAC addresses are used to specify both the destination and the source of each data packet.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] Ethernet establishes link-level connections, which can be defined using both the destination and source addresses.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] On reception of a transmission, the receiver uses the destination address to determine whether the transmission is relevant to the station or should be ignored.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] A network interface normally does not accept packets addressed to other Ethernet stations.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] An EtherType field in each frame is used by the operating system on the receiving station to select the appropriate protocol module (e.g., an Internet Protocol version such as IPv4).
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] Ethernet frames are said to be *self-identifying*, because of the EtherType field.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] Self-identifying frames make it possible to intermix multiple protocols on the same physical network and allow a single computer to use multiple protocols together.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] Despite the evolution of Ethernet technology, all generations of Ethernet (excluding early experimental versions) use the same frame formats.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] Mixed-speed networks can be built using Ethernet switches and repeaters supporting the desired Ethernet variants.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] Due to the ubiquity of Ethernet and the ever-decreasing cost of the hardware needed to support it, by 2004 most manufacturers built Ethernet interfaces directly into PC motherboards, eliminating the need for a separate network card.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] Ethernet was originally based on the idea of computers communicating over a shared coaxial cable acting as a broadcast transmission medium.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] The method used was similar to those used in radio systems, with the common cable providing the communication channel likened to the *Luminiferous aether* in 19th-century physics, and it was from this reference that the name *Ethernet* was derived.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] The original Ethernet's shared coaxial cable (the shared medium) traversed a building or campus to connect every attached machine.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] A scheme known as carrier-sense multiple access with collision detection (CSMA/CD) governed the way the computers shared the channel.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] This scheme was simpler than competing Token Ring or Token Bus technologies.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] Computers are connected to an Attachment Unit Interface (AUI) transceiver, which is in turn connected to the cable (with thin Ethernet, the transceiver is usually integrated into the network adapter).
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] While a simple passive wire is highly reliable for small networks, it is not reliable for large extended networks, where damage to the wire in a single place, or a single bad connector, can make the whole Ethernet segment unusable.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] Through the first half of the 1980s, Ethernet's 10BASE5 implementation utilised a coaxial cable 0.375 inches (9.5 mm) in diameter, later referred to as *thick Ethernet* or *thicknet*.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] Its successor, 10BASE2, called *thin Ethernet* or *thinnet*, used the RG-58 coaxial cable.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] The emphasis was on making installation of the cable easier and less costly.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] Since all communication happens on the same wire, any information sent by one computer is received by all, even if that information is intended for just one destination.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] The network interface card interrupts the CPU only when applicable packets are received: the card ignores information not addressed to it.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] Use of a single cable also means that the data bandwidth is shared, such that, for example, available data bandwidth to each device is halved when two stations are simultaneously active.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] A collision happens when two stations attempt to transmit at the same time.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] They corrupt transmitted data and require stations to re-transmit.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] The loss of data and retransmission reduce throughput.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] In the worst case, where multiple active hosts connected with maximum allowed cable length attempt to transmit many short frames, excessive collisions can reduce throughput dramatically.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] However, a Xerox report in 1980, published in Communications of the ACM, studied the performance of an existing Ethernet installation under both normal and artificially generated heavy load.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] The report claimed that 98% throughput on the LAN was observed.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] This is in contrast with token passing LANs (Token Ring, Token Bus), all of which suffer throughput degradation as each new node comes into the LAN, due to token waits.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] This report was controversial, as modeling showed that collision-based networks theoretically became unstable under loads as low as 37% of nominal capacity.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] Many early researchers failed to understand these results.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] Performance on real networks is significantly better.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] In a modern Ethernet, the stations do not all share one channel through a shared cable or a simple repeater hub; instead, each station communicates with a switch, which in turn forwards that traffic to the destination station.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] In this topology, collisions are only possible if the station and switch attempt to communicate with each other at the same time, and collisions are limited to this link.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] Furthermore, the 10BASE-T standard introduced a full duplex mode of operation, which became familiar with Fast Ethernet and the de facto standard with Gigabit Ethernet.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] In full duplex, a switch and a station can send and receive simultaneously, and therefore modern Ethernet networks are completely collision-free.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] For signal degradation and timing reasons, coaxial Ethernet segments have a restricted size.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] Somewhat larger networks can be built by using an Ethernet repeater.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] Early repeaters had only two ports, allowing, at most, a doubling of network size.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] Once repeaters with more than two ports became available, it was possible to wire the network in a star topology.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] Early experiments with star topologies (called *Fibernet*) using optical fiber were published by 1978.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] Shared cable Ethernet is always hard to install in offices because its bus topology is in conflict with the star topology cable plans designed into buildings for telephony.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] Modifying Ethernet to conform to twisted-pair telephone wiring already installed in commercial buildings provided another opportunity to lower costs, expand the installed base, and leverage building design, and, thus, twisted-pair Ethernet was the next logical development in the mid-1980s.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] Ethernet on unshielded twisted-pair cables (UTP) began with StarLAN at 1 Mbit/s in the mid-1980s.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] In 1987 SynOptics introduced the first twisted-pair Ethernet at 10 Mbit/s in a star-wired cabling topology with a central hub, later called LattisNet.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] These evolved into 10BASE-T, which was designed for point-to-point links only, and all termination was built into the device.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] This changed repeaters from a specialist device used at the center of large networks to a device that every twisted pair-based network with more than two machines had to use.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] The tree structure that resulted from this made Ethernet networks easier to maintain by preventing most faults with one peer or its associated cable from affecting other devices on the network.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] Every packet is sent to every other port on the repeater, so bandwidth and security problems are not addressed.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] The total throughput of the repeater is limited to that of a single link, and all links must operate at the same speed.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] While repeaters can isolate some aspects of Ethernet segments, such as cable breakages, they still forward all traffic to all Ethernet devices.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] The entire network is one collision domain, and all hosts have to be able to detect collisions anywhere on the network.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] This limits the number of repeaters between the farthest nodes and creates practical limits on how many machines can communicate on an Ethernet network.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] Segments joined by repeaters have to all operate at the same speed, making phased-in upgrades impossible.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] To alleviate these problems, bridging was created to communicate at the data link layer while isolating the physical layer.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] With bridging, only well-formed Ethernet packets are forwarded from one Ethernet segment to another; collisions and packet errors are isolated.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] At initial startup, Ethernet bridges work somewhat like Ethernet repeaters, passing all traffic between segments.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] By observing the source addresses of incoming frames, the bridge then builds an address table associating addresses to segments.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] Once an address is learned, the bridge forwards network traffic destined for that address only to the associated segment, improving overall performance.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] Broadcast traffic is still forwarded to all network segments.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] Bridges also overcome the limits on total segments between two hosts and allow the mixing of speeds, both of which are critical to the incremental deployment of faster Ethernet variants.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] In 1989, Motorola Codex introduced their 6310 EtherSpan, and Kalpana introduced their EtherSwitch; these were examples of the first commercial Ethernet switches.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] Early switches such as this used cut-through switching where only the header of the incoming packet is examined before it is either dropped or forwarded to another segment.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] One drawback of this method is that it does not readily allow a mixture of different link speeds.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] Another is that packets that have been corrupted are still propagated through the network.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] The eventual remedy for this was a return to the original store and forward approach of bridging, where the packet is read into a buffer on the switch in its entirety, its frame check sequence verified and only then the packet is forwarded.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] In modern network equipment, this process is typically done using application-specific integrated circuits allowing packets to be forwarded at wire speed.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] When a twisted pair or fiber link segment is used, and neither end is connected to a repeater, full-duplex Ethernet becomes possible over that segment.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] In full-duplex mode, both devices can transmit and receive to and from each other at the same time, and there is no collision domain.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] This doubles the aggregate bandwidth of the link and is sometimes advertised as double the link speed (for example, 200 Mbit/s for Fast Ethernet).
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] The elimination of the collision domain for these connections also means that all the link's bandwidth can be used by the two devices on that segment and that segment length is not limited by the constraints of collision detection.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] Since packets are typically delivered only to the port they are intended for, traffic on a switched Ethernet is less public than on shared-medium Ethernet.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] Despite this, switched Ethernet should still be regarded as an insecure network technology, because it is easy to subvert switched Ethernet systems by means such as ARP spoofing and MAC flooding.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] The bandwidth advantages, the improved isolation of devices from each other, the ability to easily mix different speeds of devices and the elimination of the chaining limits inherent in non-switched Ethernet have made switched Ethernet the dominant network technology.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] Advanced networking features in switches use Shortest Path Bridging (SPB) or the Spanning Tree Protocol (STP) to maintain a loop-free, meshed network, allowing physical loops for redundancy (STP) or load-balancing (SPB).
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] Shortest Path Bridging includes the use of the link-state routing protocol IS-IS to allow larger networks with shortest path routes between devices.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] In 2016, Ethernet replaced InfiniBand as the most popular system interconnect of TOP500 supercomputers.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] In many industrial systems, Ethernet and fieldbus coexist, each performing certain roles, and data is exchanged between them through gateways.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] The Ethernet physical layer evolved over a considerable time span and encompasses coaxial, twisted pair and fiber-optic physical media interfaces, with speeds from 1 Mbit/s to 400 Gbit/s.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] The first introduction of twisted-pair CSMA/CD was StarLAN, standardized as 802.3 1BASE5.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] While 1BASE5 had little market penetration, it defined the physical apparatus (wire, plug/jack, pin-out, and wiring plan) that would be carried over to 10BASE-T through 10GBASE-T.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] The most common forms used are 10BASE-T, 100BASE-TX, and 1000BASE-T.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] All three use twisted-pair cables and 8P8C modular connectors.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] They run at 10 Mbit/s, 100 Mbit/s, and 1 Gbit/s, respectively.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] Fiber optic variants of Ethernet (that commonly use SFP modules) are also very popular in larger networks, offering high performance, better electrical isolation and longer distance (tens of kilometers with some versions).
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] In general, network protocol stack software will work similarly on all varieties.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] In IEEE 802.3, a datagram is called a packet or frame.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] *Packet* is used to describe the overall transmission unit and includes the preamble, start frame delimiter (SFD) and carrier extension (if present).
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] The *frame* begins after the start frame delimiter with a frame header featuring source and destination MAC addresses and the EtherType field giving either the protocol type for the payload protocol or the length of the payload.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] The middle section of the frame consists of payload data, including any headers for other protocols (for example, Internet Protocol) carried in the frame.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] The frame ends with a 32-bit cyclic redundancy check, which is used to detect corruption of data in transit.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] Notably, Ethernet packets have no time-to-live field, leading to possible problems in the presence of a switching loop.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] Autonegotiation is the procedure by which two connected devices choose common transmission parameters, e.g., speed and duplex mode.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] Autonegotiation was initially an optional feature, first introduced with 100BASE-TX (1995 IEEE 802.3u Fast Ethernet standard), and is backward compatible with 10BASE-T.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] The specification was improved in the 1998 release of IEEE 802.3.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] Autonegotiation is mandatory for 1000BASE-T and faster.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] A switching loop or bridge loop occurs in computer networks when there is more than one Layer 2 (OSI model) path between two endpoints (e.g., multiple connections between two network switches or two ports on the same switch connected to each other).
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] The loop creates broadcast storms as broadcasts and multicasts are forwarded by switches out every port, the switch or switches will repeatedly rebroadcast the broadcast messages flooding the network.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] Since the Layer 2 header does not support a *time to live* (TTL) value, if a frame is sent into a looped topology, it can loop forever.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] A physical topology that contains switching or bridge loops is attractive for redundancy reasons, yet a switched network must not have loops.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] The solution is to allow physical loops, but create a loop-free logical topology using the SPB protocol or the older STP on the network switches.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] A node that is sending longer than the maximum transmission window for an Ethernet packet is considered to be *jabbering*.
[src:doip-diagnostics/ethernet] Depending on the physical topology, jabber detection and remedy differ somewhat.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] OBD systems give the vehicle owner or repair technician access to the status of the various vehicle sub-systems.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] The amount of diagnostic information available via OBD has varied widely since its introduction in the early 1980s versions of onboard vehicle computers.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] Early versions of OBD would simply illuminate a tell-tale light if a problem was detected, but would not provide any information as to the nature of the problem.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] Modern OBD implementations use a standardized digital communications port to provide real-time data and diagnostic trouble codes which allow malfunctions within the vehicle to be rapidly identified.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] GM's ALDL (Assembly Line Diagnostic Link) is sometimes referred to as a predecessor to, or a manufacturer's proprietary version of, an OBD-I diagnostic starting in 1981.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] This interface was made in different varieties and changed with power train control modules (aka PCM, ECM, ECU).
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] Different versions had slight differences in pin-outs and baud rates.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] Earlier versions used a 160 baud rate, while later versions went up to 8192 baud and used bi-directional communications to the PCM.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] The regulatory intent of OBD-I was to encourage auto manufacturers to design reliable emission control systems that remain effective for the vehicle's "useful life".
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] The hope was that by forcing annual emissions testing for California starting in 1988, and denying registration to vehicles that did not pass, drivers would tend to purchase vehicles that would more reliably pass the test.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] OBD-I was largely unsuccessful, as the means of reporting emissions-specific diagnostic information was not standardized.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] Technical difficulties with obtaining standardized and reliable emissions information from all vehicles led to an inability to implement the annual testing program effectively.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] The Diagnostic Trouble Codes (DTCs) of OBD-I vehicles can usually be found without an expensive scan tool.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] Each manufacturer used their own Diagnostic Link Connector (DLC), DLC location, DTC definitions, and procedure to read the DTCs from the vehicle.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] DTCs from OBD-I cars are often read through the blinking patterns of the 'Check Engine Light' (CEL) or 'Service Engine Soon' (SES) light.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] By connecting certain pins of the diagnostic connector, the 'Check Engine' light will blink out a two-digit number that corresponds to a specific error condition.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] The DTCs of some OBD-I cars are interpreted in different ways, however.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] Cadillac fuel-injected vehicles are equipped with actual *onboard* diagnostics, providing trouble codes, actuator tests and sensor data through the new digital Electronic Climate Control display.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] Holding down 'Off' and 'Warmer' for several seconds activates the diagnostic mode without the need for an external scan tool.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] Some Honda engine computers are equipped with LEDs that light up in a specific pattern to indicate the DTC.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] General Motors, some 1989–1995 Ford vehicles (DCL), and some 1989–1995 Toyota/Lexus vehicles have a live sensor data stream available; however, many other OBD-I equipped vehicles do not.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] OBD-I vehicles have fewer DTCs available than OBD-II equipped vehicles.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] OBD 1.5 refers to a partial implementation of OBD-II which General Motors used on some vehicles in 1994, 1995 & 1996 (GM did not use the term OBD 1.5 in the documentation for these vehicles — they simply had an OBD and an OBD-II section in the service manual).
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] For example, the 1994–1995 model year Corvettes have one post-catalyst oxygen sensor (although they have two catalytic converters), and have a subset of the OBD-II codes implemented.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] For ALDL connections, pin 9 is the data stream, pins 4 and 5 are ground, and pin 16 is the battery voltage.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] An OBD 1.5 compatible scan tool is required to read codes generated by OBD 1.5.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] Additional vehicle-specific diagnostic and control circuits are also available on this connector.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] For instance, on the Corvette there are interfaces for the Class 2 serial data stream from the PCM, the CCM diagnostic terminal, the radio data stream, the airbag system, the selective ride control system, the low tire pressure warning system, and the passive keyless entry system.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] An OBD 1.5 has also been used in the Ford Scorpio since 95.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] OBD-II is an improvement over OBD-I in both capability and standardization.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] The OBD-II standard specifies the type of diagnostic connector and its pinout, the electrical signalling protocols available, and the messaging format.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] It also provides a candidate list of vehicle parameters to monitor along with how to encode the data for each.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] There is a pin in the connector that provides power for the scan tool from the vehicle battery, which eliminates the need to connect a scan tool to a power source separately.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] However, some technicians might still connect the scan tool to an auxiliary power source to protect data in the unusual event that a vehicle experiences a loss of electrical power due to a malfunction.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] Finally, the OBD-II standard provides an extensible list of DTCs.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] As a result of this standardization, a single device can query the on-board computer(s) in any vehicle.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] This OBD-II came in two models OBD-IIA and OBD-IIB.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] OBD-II standardization was prompted by emissions requirements, and though only emission-related codes and data are required to be transmitted through it, most manufacturers have made the OBD-II Data Link Connector the only one in the vehicle through which all systems are diagnosed and programmed.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] OBD-II Diagnostic Trouble Codes are 4-digit, preceded by a letter: P for powertrain (engine and transmission), B for body, C for chassis, and U for network.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] The OBD-II specification provides for a standardized hardware interface — the female 16-pin (2x8) J1962 connector, where type A is used for 12-volt vehicles and type B for 24-volt vehicles.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] Unlike the OBD-I connector, which was sometimes found under the bonnet of the vehicle, the OBD-II connector is required to be within 2 feet (0.61 m) of the steering wheel (unless an exemption is applied for by the manufacturer, in which case it is still somewhere within reach of the driver).
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] The assignment of unspecified pins is left to the vehicle manufacturer's discretion.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] For newly introduced models, the regulation dates applied a year earlier – January 1, 2000 for petrol and January 1, 2003, for diesel.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] For passenger cars with a Gross Vehicle Weight rating of greater than 2500 kg and for light commercial vehicles, the regulation dates applied from January 1, 2002, for petrol models, and January 1, 2007, for diesel models.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] The technical implementation of EOBD is essentially the same as OBD-II, with the same SAE J1962 diagnostic link connector and signal protocols being used.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] With Euro V and Euro VI emission standards, EOBD emission thresholds are lower than previous Euro III and IV.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] Each of the EOBD fault codes consists of five characters: a letter, followed by four numbers.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] The letter refers to the system being interrogated e.g.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] Pxxxx would refer to the powertrain system.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] The next character would be a 0 if complies to the EOBD standard.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] The next character would refer to the sub system.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] The following two characters would refer to the individual fault within each subsystem.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] The term "EOBD2" is marketing speak used by some vehicle manufacturers to refer to manufacturer-specific features that are not actually part of the OBD or EOBD standard.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] JOBD is a version of OBD-II for vehicles sold in Japan.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] The ADR 79/01 Vehicle Standard (**A**ustralian **D**esign **R**ule **79/01** – Emission Control for Light Vehicles, 2005) is the Australian equivalent of OBD-II.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] It applies to all vehicles of category M1 and N1 with a Gross Vehicle Weight rating of 3,500 kg (7,700 lb) or less, registered from new within Australia and produced since January 1, 2006 for petrol-engined cars and since January 1, 2007 for diesel-engined cars.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] For newly introduced models, the regulation dates applied a year earlier – January 1, 2005 for petrol and January 1, 2006, for diesel.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] The ADR 79/01 standard was supplemented by the ADR 79/02 standard which imposed tighter emissions restrictions, applicable to all vehicles of class M1 and N1 with a Gross Vehicle Weight rating of 3500 kg or less, from July 1, 2008, for new models, July 1, 2010, for all models.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] The technical implementation of this standard is essentially the same as OBD-II, with the same SAE J1962 diagnostic link connector and signal protocols being used.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] In North America, EMD and EMD+ are on-board diagnostic systems that were used on vehicles with a gross vehicle weight rating of 14,000 lb (6,400 kg) or more between the 2007 and 2012 model years if those vehicles did not already implement OBD-II.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] EMD was used on California emissions vehicles between model years 2007 and 2009 that did not already have OBD-II.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] EMD was required to monitor fuel delivery, exhaust gas recirculation, the diesel particulate filter (on diesel engines), and emissions-related powertrain control module inputs and outputs for circuit continuity, data rationality, and output functionality.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] EMD+ was used on model year 2010-2012 California and Federal petrol-engined vehicles with a gross vehicle weight rating of over 14,000 lb (6,400 kg), it added the ability to monitor nitrogen oxide catalyst performance.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] EMD and EMD+ are similar to OBD-I in logic but use the same SAE J1962 data connector and CAN bus as OBD-II systems.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] Five signaling protocols are permitted with the OBD-II interface.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] Most vehicles implement only one of the protocols.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] All OBD-II pinouts use the same connector, but different pins are used with the exception of pin 4 (battery ground) and pin 16 (battery positive).
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] OBD-II provides access to data from the engine control unit (ECU) and offers a valuable source of information when troubleshooting problems inside a vehicle.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] The SAE J1979 standard defines a method for requesting various diagnostic data and a list of standard parameters that might be available from the ECU.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] The various available parameters are addressed by "parameter identification numbers" or **PID**s which are defined in J1979.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] For a list of basic PIDs, their definitions, and the formula to convert raw OBD-II output to meaningful diagnostic units, see OBD-II PIDs.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] Manufacturers are not required to implement all PIDs listed in J1979 and they are allowed to include proprietary PIDs that are not listed.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] The PID request and data retrieval system gives access to real time performance data as well as flagged DTCs.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] For a list of generic OBD-II DTCs suggested by the SAE, see #OBD-II diagnostic trouble codes.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] Individual manufacturers often enhance the OBD-II code set with additional proprietary DTCs.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] Here is a basic introduction to the OBD communication protocol according to ISO 15031.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] In SAE J1979 these "modes" were renamed to "services", starting in 2003.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] Various tools are available that plug into the OBD connector to access OBD functions.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] These range from simple generic consumer-level tools to sophisticated OEM dealership tools and vehicle telematic devices.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] A range of hand-held scan tools is available.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] Mobile device applications allow mobile devices such as cell phones and tablets to display and manipulate OBD-II data accessed via USB adaptor cables or Bluetooth adapters plugged into the car's OBD II connector.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] Newer devices on the market are equipped with GPS sensors and the ability to transmit vehicle location and diagnostics data over a cellular network.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] Modern OBD-II devices can be used for locating vehicles and monitoring driving behavior in addition to reading Diagnostic Trouble Codes (DTC).
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] More advanced devices allow users to reset engine DTCs, effectively turning off engine lights in the dashboard; however, resetting the codes does not address the underlying issues and can lead to engine damage if a serious issue is left unattended.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] An OBD-II software package, when installed on a computer (Windows, Mac, or Linux), can help diagnose the onboard system, read and erase DTCs, turn off the MIL, show real-time data, and measure vehicle fuel economy.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] Using OBD-II software requires an OBD-II adapter (commonly using Bluetooth, Wi-Fi or USB) plugged into the OBD-II port to enable the vehicle to connect with the computer where the software is installed.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] A PC-based OBD analysis tool converts the OBD-II signals to a serial data format (USB or serial port) readable by PCs or Macs.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] The software then decodes the received data for visual display.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] Many interfaces are based on the ELM327 or STN OBD interpreter ICs, both of which read all five generic OBD-II protocols.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] Some adapters now use the J2534 API, allowing them to access OBD-II protocols for both cars and trucks.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] The extent that a PC tool may access manufacturer- or vehicle-specific ECU diagnostics varies between software products as it does between hand-held scanners.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] Data loggers are designed to capture vehicle data while the vehicle is in normal operation for later analysis.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] Analysis of vehicle black box data may be performed periodically, automatically transmitted wirelessly to a third party, or retrieved for forensic analysis after an event such as an accident, traffic infringement, or mechanical fault.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] In the United States, many states now use OBD-II testing instead of tailpipe testing in OBD-II-compliant vehicles (1996 and newer).
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] Since OBD-II stores trouble codes for emissions equipment, the testing computer can query the vehicle's onboard computer and verify there are no emission-related trouble codes and that the vehicle is in compliance with emission standards for the model year it was manufactured.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] In the Netherlands, 2006 and later vehicles get a yearly EOBD emission check.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] Auto enthusiasts have traditionally installed additional gauges such as for manifold vacuum or battery current.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] The OBD standard interface has enabled a new generation of enthusiast instrumentation accessing the full range of vehicle data used for diagnostics, as well as derived data such as instantaneous fuel economy.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] Instrumentation may take the form of dedicated trip computers, carputers, or interfaces to PDAs, smartphones, or a Garmin navigation unit.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] As a carputer is essentially a PC, the same software could be loaded as for PC-based scan tools and vice versa; the distinction lies in the software's intended use.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] These enthusiast systems may also include some functionality similar to the other scan tools.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] OBD II information is a data source for fleet telematics systems.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] Devices that perform fleet management functions such as fleet tracking, monitoring fuel efficiency, and preventing unsafe driving often connect to the OBD-II port.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] The port is also used for remote diagnostics and by pay-as-you-drive insurance.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] Hundreds of different hardware manufacturers produce OBD-II telematics devices.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] These devices vary in their capabilities.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] Some simpler GPS tracking devices use the OBD-II port only as a convenient source of power.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] More advanced devices, such as a telematic control unit, are able to access the vehicle's internal network to capture and decode a wide range of operational data.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] Commonly supported OBD II data such as vehicle speed, RPM, and fuel level allow these devices to monitor vehicle idling times, speeding, and over-revving.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] Monitoring OBD II DTCs can alert a company to a vehicle's engine problems by providing the relevant diagnostic code.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] Other sensor data from the port can be used to detect unsafe driving in real time.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] This detection is done by adding a complex events processor (CEP) to the backend and on the client's interface.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] OBD II is also monitored to block mobile phones when driving and to record trip data for insurance purposes.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] OBD-II diagnostic trouble codes (DTCs) are five characters long, with the first letter indicating a category, and the remaining four being a hexadecimal number.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] The first character, representing category can only be one of the following four letters, given here with their associated meanings.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] (This restriction in number is due to how only two bits of memory are used to indicate the category when DTCs are stored and transmitted).
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] The second character is a number in the range of 0–3.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] (This restriction is again due to memory storage limitations).
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] The third character may denote a particular vehicle system that the fault relates to.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] Finally the fourth and fifth characters define the exact problem detected.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] In 2012, researchers at the University of Washington and University of California examined the security around OBD and found that they were able to gain control over many vehicle components via the interface.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] Furthermore, they were able to upload new firmware into the engine control units.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] Their conclusion is that vehicle embedded systems are not designed with security in mind.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] There have been reports of thieves using specialist OBD reprogramming devices to enable them to steal cars without the use of a key.
[src:doip-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] The primary causes of this vulnerability lie in the tendency for vehicle manufacturers to extend the bus for purposes other than those for which it was designed, and the lack of authentication and authorization in the OBD specifications, which instead rely largely on security through obscurity.
[src:doip-diagnostics/unified-diagnostic-services] The term "unified" refers to the fact that UDS is an international standard rather than a manufacturer-specific protocol.
[src:doip-diagnostics/unified-diagnostic-services] Today, nearly all Tier 1 suppliers implement UDS in ECUs developed for automotive original equipment manufacturers (OEMs).
[src:doip-diagnostics/unified-diagnostic-services] UDS is also integrated into larger software architectures, including AUTOSAR.
[src:doip-diagnostics/unified-diagnostic-services] Modern vehicles have a diagnostic interface for on-board diagnostics, which makes it possible to connect a computer (client) or diagnostics tool, which is referred to as tester, to the communication system of the vehicle.
[src:doip-diagnostics/unified-diagnostic-services] Thus, UDS requests can be sent to the controllers which provide responses (this may be positive or negative).
[src:doip-diagnostics/unified-diagnostic-services] Request messages are transmitted by a Client towards one or more Servers.
[src:doip-diagnostics/unified-diagnostic-services] Service Identifier (SID) is the first byte in each request message.
[src:doip-diagnostics/unified-diagnostic-services] Response messages are transmitted by Servers to a Client.
[src:doip-diagnostics/unified-diagnostic-services] The first byte in the response message is usually Response Service Identifier (RSID) value (with the exception of following responses to ReadDataByPeriodicIdentifier service).
[src:doip-diagnostics/unified-diagnostic-services] Format of each positive response message is specific for the diagnostic service it relates to.
[src:doip-diagnostics/unified-diagnostic-services] Negative Response Codes (NRC in short) carry the information for request message rejection.
